data.title: Chynna Rogers, rapper and model, dies at 25
data.meta_description: Chynna Rogers, a 25-year-old model-turned-rapper, has died at her home in Philadelphia.
data.text:
Chynna Rogers, a 25-year-old model-turned-rapper, has died at her home in Philadelphia.

"I can regrettably confirm Chynna passed away," Rogers' manager John Miller confirmed to The Wrap. "Chynna was deeply loved and will be sorely missed."

The cause of Rogers death has been confirmed as an accidental drug overdose based on Philadelphia Department of Public Health, NBC reported on April 10.

The 'Mood' singer was born in Philadelphia and started her career as a model after being signed to Ford Models at 14 years of age.

READ MORE: Rihanna's father thought he was going to die after being diagnosed with coronavirus

Rogers eventually collaborated with late record producer A$AP Yams who was part of the hip-hop group A$AP Mob. He tragically died of a drug overdose in 2015.

She released many EP's including I'm Not Here. She went on release This Isn't Happening in 2015 and music 2 die 2 in 2016.

She was became known for her some of her earlier hit singles like 'Selfie' and 'Glen Coco.'

Rogers opened up about her ambitions, her history of drug addiction and the death of her mother in an 2018 interview with Pitchfork.

"My mom would be really tight with me if I used her as an excuse to fall off," she said. "It's just more reason to work and get this s--- done. I didn't feel like I deserved to be making a living off talking about my life yet because I just couldn't relate to enough people.

"It wasn't just the drug-addict thing, but also all the behaviours that come with it, all the situations you end up in, and the people you end up around just living that life."

If you, or someone you know would like to talk to someone confidentially about addiction, contact Lifeline on 13 11 14 or visit Reach Out. In an emergency, call 000.
